metadata.name: barcode(fxhash) #412
metadata.description:
[UPDATED: There was a bug in the first edition of this token that has been solved in this. All minters of the previous edition, has a reserve of 2]

barcode(fxhash) converts the ascii characters from the transaction hash of the token (fxhash variable) into barcodes for each of 51 characters. It uses Code 39 (https://github.com/graphicore/librebarcode), so it is not case sensitive. Each iteration has from 1 to 8 columns, and from 1 to 8 rows, and the frist N characters of the fxhash are displayed in one of first N positions (first 2 characters are discarted). If the number of characters is greater than 49 (length of fxhash discarting 'oo'), the boxes will continue to be filled, returning from the third character of fxhash.

Features generated by fxrand() random function:

-num_chars: number of characters displayed. from 1 to 64. They are the first N characters of fxhash.
-has_fxhash: this boolean value indicates whether fxhash contains the letters needed to form the word 'fxhash'.
-show_fxhash: this boolean value indicates whether fxhash contains the letters needed to form the word 'fxhash' and these are all displayed.
-columns: number of columns (1-8).
-rows: number of rows (1-8).
-color_mode: color mode white (light) or black (dark).
-separacio: factor of separation between barcodes (1.1, 1.5 or 2)
-scale_type: scale type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)
-rotate_type: rotation type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)
-transparent: this boolean value indicates whether the barcodes has a transparent background.
-squares: this boolean value indicates whether the barcodes width=height.
-main_shadow: blur value for main shadow.
-exterior_shadow: exterior shadow type rotation type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)
-interior_shadow: exterior shadow type rotation type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)


(There are more values generated by fxrand() not shown as Feature)

click to show all fxhash barcodes, wich are displayed.

metadata.name: Influence no.4: Linear Composition #86
metadata.description:
This is the latest set of the "influence" series. "Linear composition" is an exploration of creating a highly detailed abstract artwork using a very large matrix of small circular shapes that are colored based on a division algorithm, each having a different shape. It is also inspired by old dot-matrix printers that create a pattern of dots when printing. To see the artwork in detail, open it in high quality and zoom in. Various densities and more than 12 color palettes have been used.

-----------

- Add &density=2 to 12 to the live view URL to render the image at higher resolution.

- Press ‚Äôs‚Äô on the live mode to save the artwork.

  Made with p5js.

metadata.name: The Spectrum Of Nature #12
metadata.description:
*\_../*`¬¨-‚Äô\/*`¬¨‚Äô‚Äô¬¨`*\/‚Äô-¬¨`*\.._/*

Nature, nature, evolving might‚Ä¶ Silent inventor, always right.
Where is the edge of nature and where do we begin?  
What is of nature and what is of man? 
Isn't everything made by nature's hands?

To know more about the concept and technicalities of this piece, see the fxtext article ‚ÄúThe spectrum of nature - a short making of‚Äù. Link at the bottom. If you‚Äôd rather just ignore my personal meaning, feel free to skip the article. 

\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\

Basic info:
The piece comes in possible portrait or landscape versions. Both have a relative size of 1 by 1.5. So the initial render will be 1000px wide and 1500px high for portrait. And 1500x1000 for landscape. With the ability to scale this up (see below).

The piece uses WebGL, so will perform much better with a graphics card. A faster computer will obviously be better, though I've done my very best to make it fast and efficient for any old laptop. My hope is that you will find the render process quick and enjoyable for the amount of detail that‚Äôs present. 

../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\../‚Äô`*‚Äô`\..

Controls:
Press the [s] key to save the initial render. You will need to wait a few seconds after all the elements have stopped loading. A box will pop up in the top left saying ‚Äúdone‚Äù for 4 seconds when it‚Äôs ready. For the [s] key to work you may need to open in a new tab. But can right click save otherwise.

Larger sizes:
Press the [2-9] keys to save a resolution of that key size. So [2] saves a 2000x3000 size image, [9] saves a 9000x13500 size image etc. Unless you are making some very large prints you probably won‚Äôt need more than 4k (even 2-3k is big). Though the option is there. 

There may be slight variations in the textures for the larger renders, this is because the shader code has to redraw the textures at the higher pixel resolution, and getting the textures where they sit is more of an art than a science. All the elements remain exact however. 

/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*/*

Made with javascript and some small extra code:
A palette creator by @nathansonic
Noisejs - github.com/josephg/noisejs - Perlin noise generator
Twgl - github.com/greggman/twgl.js - A small webGL helper.
